        "---\n",
        "title: \"Day 02: Bouncing Ball Physics 🏀\"\n",
        "subtitle: \"Discover the Magic of Velocity and Gravity!\"\n",
        "author: \"Pygame Tutorial Series\"\n",
        "format:\n",
        "  html:\n",
        "    theme: light\n",
        "    toc: true\n",
        "    toc-depth: 3\n",
        "    code-copy: true\n",
        "    css: ../../shared/styles/tutorial.css\n",
        "execute:\n",
        "  enabled: true\n",
        "  cache: false\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.hero-banner}\n",
        "# 🏀 Welcome to Day 02!\n",
        "\n",
        "Today, you'll create a **physics simulation** with bouncing balls! You'll learn about velocity, acceleration, gravity, and friction. By the end of this tutorial, you'll have balls bouncing realistically around your screen!\n",
        "\n",
        "**Time Required:** ~45 minutes  \n",
        "**Difficulty:** Beginner 🌟\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 🎯 What You'll Learn Today\n",
        "\n",
        "By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:\n",
        "\n",
        "- ✅ Understand **velocity** and **acceleration**\n",
        "- ✅ Implement **gravity** in your games\n",
        "- ✅ Create **realistic bouncing** with energy loss\n",
        "- ✅ Work with **multiple objects** at once\n",
        "- ✅ Add **interactive elements** (spawn balls with mouse clicks)\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 📚 Quick Recap: What We Learned in Day 01\n",
        "\n",
        "Yesterday, we covered:\n",
        "- Setting up a Pygame project with UV\n",
        "- Creating game windows and the game loop\n",
        "- Handling keyboard input\n",
        "- Basic collision detection\n",
        "\n",
        "Today builds on these concepts with physics!\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 🎓 Part 1: Understanding Physics in Games (10 minutes)\n",
        "\n",
        "### What is Velocity?\n",
        "\n",
        "**Velocity** describes how fast something is moving and in what direction.\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Horizontal velocity (vx)**: How fast something moves left/right\n",
        "- **Vertical velocity (vy)**: How fast something moves up/down\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## 🎯 What This Code Demonstrates\n",
        "\n",
        "This example shows how **velocity changes position over time**. We'll:\n",
        "1. Create an object at position (100, 100)\n",
        "2. Give it velocity: moving right (+5) and up (-3) each frame\n",
        "3. Update its position 5 times and watch it move!\n",
        "\n",
        "**Key idea:** Position changes by velocity amount every frame. After 5 frames with vx=5, the object moves 25 pixels right!\n",
        ":::"
      ],
      "id": "99c688bd"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Let's explore velocity!\n",
        "# Think of velocity as \"how many pixels to move each frame\"\n",
        "\n",
        "class SimpleObject:\n",
        "    def __init__(self, x, y):\n",
        "        self.x = x\n",
        "        self.y = y\n",
        "        self.vx = 5   # Moving right at 5 pixels/frame\n",
        "        self.vy = -3  # Moving up at 3 pixels/frame\n",
        "    \n",
        "    def update(self):\n",
        "        \"\"\"Update position based on velocity\"\"\"\n",
        "        self.x += self.vx\n",
        "        self.y += self.vy\n",
        "        \n",
        "    def __str__(self):\n",
        "        return f\"Position: ({self.x:.1f}, {self.y:.1f})\"\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create object and simulate 5 frames\n",
        "obj = SimpleObject(100, 100)\n",
        "print(\"Starting:\", obj)\n",
        "\n",
        "for frame in range(1, 6):\n",
        "    obj.update()\n",
        "    print(f\"Frame {frame}:\", obj)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"\\nTotal distance moved: X={obj.vx * 5}, Y={obj.vy * 5}\")"
      ],
      "id": "5b05c9e0",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "::: {.callout-important}\n",
        "## 📖 What The Output Tells Us\n",
        "\n",
        "**Reading the results:**\n",
        "- **Starting:** (100.0, 100.0)\n",
        "- **Frame 1:** (105.0, 97.0) - moved 5 right, 3 up\n",
        "- **Frame 2:** (110.0, 94.0) - moved another 5 right, 3 up\n",
        "- **Frame 5:** (125.0, 85.0) - total of 25 right, 15 up\n",
        "\n",
        "**How it works:**\n",
        "1. Each `update()` call adds velocity to position\n",
        "2. Positive vx (+5) moves right, negative vy (-3) moves up\n",
        "3. After 5 frames: x increased by 25 (5×5), y decreased by 15 (3×5)\n",
        "\n",
        "**Real game example:** This is how a bouncing ball or flying bird moves across the screen! The game calls `update()` 60 times per second, creating smooth motion.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Try mentally:** If vx was 10, where would x be after 5 frames?\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-consider}\n",
        "## 🤔 Consider This Corner\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why use negative velocity for \"up\"?**\n",
        "\n",
        "Remember from Day 01: In Pygame, Y=0 is at the **top** of the screen, and Y increases **downward**. So to move up, we need negative Y velocity!\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "### What is Acceleration?\n",
        "\n",
        "**Acceleration** is the change in velocity over time. Gravity is a constant downward acceleration!\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## 🌎 Understanding Gravity in Code\n",
        "\n",
        "Gravity is what makes objects fall! In our simulation:\n",
        "1. **Start with zero velocity** - object isn't moving yet\n",
        "2. **Each frame, gravity increases velocity** - the object speeds up\n",
        "3. **Velocity changes position** - the faster it falls, the more distance it covers\n",
        "\n",
        "**Real world:** When you drop a ball, it starts slow but gets faster as it falls. That's acceleration!\n",
        ":::"
      ],
      "id": "41788eb6"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Simulating gravity\n",
        "# Watch how velocity increases over time, making the object fall faster!\n",
        "\n",
        "class FallingObject:\n",
        "    def __init__(self, x, y):\n",
        "        self.x = x\n",
        "        self.y = y\n",
        "        self.vy = 0  # Start with no velocity\n",
        "        self.gravity = 0.5  # Acceleration due to gravity\n",
        "    \n",
        "    def update(self):\n",
        "        \"\"\"Apply gravity and update position\"\"\"\n",
        "        self.vy += self.gravity  # Velocity increases\n",
        "        self.y += self.vy        # Position changes by velocity\n",
        "        \n",
        "    def __str__(self):\n",
        "        return f\"Y: {self.y:.1f}, Velocity: {self.vy:.1f}\"\n",
        "\n",
        "# Simulate falling for 10 frames\n",
        "obj = FallingObject(0, 0)\n",
        "print(\"Falling object:\")\n",
        "for frame in range(10):\n",
        "    print(f\"Frame {frame}: {obj}\")\n",
        "    obj.update()"
      ],
      "id": "ed4c08a3",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "::: {.callout-important}\n",
        "## 📖 Analyzing the Falling Motion\n",
        "\n",
        "**What the numbers show:**\n",
        "- **Frame 0:** Y=0.0, Velocity=0.0 (not moving yet)\n",
        "- **Frame 1:** Y=0.5, Velocity=0.5 (started falling slowly)\n",
        "- **Frame 2:** Y=1.5, Velocity=1.0 (falling faster - velocity doubled!)\n",
        "- **Frame 9:** Y=22.5, Velocity=4.5 (really fast now)\n",
        "\n",
        "**The pattern:**\n",
        "1. Velocity increases by 0.5 each frame (that's our gravity value)\n",
        "2. As velocity increases, position changes more each frame\n",
        "3. This creates **accelerating motion** - getting faster over time\n",
        "\n",
        "**How the code does it:**\n",
        "```python\n",
        "self.vy += self.gravity  # Add 0.5 to velocity each frame\n",
        "self.y += self.vy         # Move by current velocity\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "**Real game use:** This makes jumping feel realistic - your character slows down as they go up, then speeds up as they fall back down!\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Notice how the velocity increases each frame, making the object fall faster and faster!\n",
        "\n",
        "### Understanding Friction and Energy Loss\n",
        "\n",
        "When a ball bounces, it doesn't bounce back to the same height because it loses energy. We simulate this with a **friction coefficient**.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## ⚽ How Bouncing Works\n",
        "\n",
        "In real life, balls lose energy when they hit the ground:\n",
        "- Some energy becomes **sound** (the bounce noise)\n",
        "- Some becomes **heat** (friction)\n",
        "- The rest stays as **motion energy**\n",
        "\n",
        "We use a **friction value of 0.8** meaning the ball keeps 80% of its energy each bounce (loses 20%).\n",
        "\n",
        "**Watch how:** Each bounce has less velocity than the last!\n",
        ":::"
      ],
      "id": "61fb67cf"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Simulating bouncing with energy loss\n",
        "# Each bounce will be weaker than the last\n",
        "\n",
        "def simulate_bounce(initial_velocity, num_bounces=5):\n",
        "    \"\"\"Simulate a bouncing ball\"\"\"\n",
        "    velocity = initial_velocity\n",
        "    height = 0\n",
        "    friction = 0.8  # Ball loses 20% energy per bounce\n",
        "    \n",
        "    print(f\"Starting velocity: {velocity}\")\n",
        "    print(\"-\" * 40)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    for bounce in range(1, num_bounces + 1):\n",
        "        # Bounce: reverse direction and apply friction\n",
        "        velocity = -velocity * friction\n",
        "        print(f\"Bounce {bounce}: velocity = {velocity:.2f}\")\n",
        "    \n",
        "    print(\"-\" * 40)\n",
        "    print(f\"Final velocity: {velocity:.2f}\")\n",
        "    print(f\"Energy remaining: {(velocity/initial_velocity)*100:.1f}%\")\n",
        "\n",
        "simulate_bounce(-15)"
      ],
      "id": "ddabca5b",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The ball keeps bouncing but each bounce is weaker!\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 🎨 Part 2: Building the Bouncing Ball Simulator (25 minutes)\n",
        "\n",
        "### Step 1: Set Up the Project\n",
        "\n",
        "First, let's understand our constants:\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "import pygame\n",
        "import sys\n",
        "import random\n",
        "\n",
        "# Initialize Pygame\n",
        "pygame.init()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Constants\n",
        "WINDOW_WIDTH = 800\n",
        "WINDOW_HEIGHT = 600\n",
        "FPS = 60\n",
        "\n",
        "# Colors\n",
        "WHITE = (255, 255, 255)\n",
        "BLACK = (0, 0, 0)\n",
        "RED = (255, 100, 100)\n",
        "BLUE = (100, 150, 255)\n",
        "GREEN = (100, 255, 150)\n",
        "PURPLE = (200, 100, 255)\n",
        "YELLOW = (255, 255, 100)\n",
        "ORANGE = (255, 165, 100)\n",
        "\n",
        "COLORS = [RED, BLUE, GREEN, PURPLE, YELLOW, ORANGE]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Physics constants\n",
        "GRAVITY = 0.5              # Acceleration (pixels/frame²)\n",
        "FRICTION = 0.99            # Energy kept after bounce (99%)\n",
        "MIN_BOUNCE_VELOCITY = 0.5  # Stop bouncing if too slow\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-tip}\n",
        "## 💡 Pro Tip\n",
        "\n",
        "Notice `FRICTION = 0.99` means the ball keeps 99% of its energy. Try different values:\n",
        "- `1.0` = Perfect bounce (no energy loss)\n",
        "- `0.8` = Bouncy ball (loses 20% energy)\n",
        "- `0.5` = Clay ball (loses 50% energy)\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "### Step 2: Create the Ball Class\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "class Ball:\n",
        "    \"\"\"Represents a bouncing ball with physics.\"\"\"\n",
        "    \n",
        "    def __init__(self, x, y, radius, color):\n",
        "        \"\"\"\n",
        "        Initialize a ball.\n",
        "        \n",
        "        Args:\n",
        "            x: Initial x position\n",
        "            y: Initial y position\n",
        "            radius: Ball radius\n",
        "            color: Ball color (RGB tuple)\n",
        "        \"\"\"\n",
        "        self.x = x\n",
        "        self.y = y\n",
        "        self.radius = radius\n",
        "        self.color = color\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Velocity (speed and direction)\n",
        "        self.vx = random.uniform(-10, 10)  # Random horizontal\n",
        "        self.vy = random.uniform(-15, -5)  # Launch upward\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "The ball starts with:\n",
        "- Random horizontal velocity (left or right)\n",
        "- Negative vertical velocity (shoots upward)\n",
        "\n",
        "### Step 3: Implement Physics Update\n",
        "\n",
        "This is where the magic happens!\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "    def update(self):\n",
        "        \"\"\"Update ball position and apply physics.\"\"\"\n",
        "        # STEP 1: Apply gravity\n",
        "        self.vy += GRAVITY\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # STEP 2: Update position based on velocity\n",
        "        self.x += self.vx\n",
        "        self.y += self.vy\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # STEP 3: Bounce off left and right walls\n",
        "        if self.x - self.radius <= 0:\n",
        "            self.x = self.radius\n",
        "            self.vx = abs(self.vx) * FRICTION\n",
        "        elif self.x + self.radius >= WINDOW_WIDTH:\n",
        "            self.x = WINDOW_WIDTH - self.radius\n",
        "            self.vx = -abs(self.vx) * FRICTION\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # STEP 4: Bounce off floor\n",
        "        if self.y + self.radius >= WINDOW_HEIGHT:\n",
        "            self.y = WINDOW_HEIGHT - self.radius\n",
        "            \n",
        "            # Only bounce if moving fast enough\n",
        "            if abs(self.vy) > MIN_BOUNCE_VELOCITY:\n",
        "                self.vy = -abs(self.vy) * FRICTION\n",
        "            else:\n",
        "                self.vy = 0  # Stop bouncing\n",
        "                \n",
        "            # Apply friction to horizontal movement\n",
        "            self.vx *= 0.95\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # STEP 5: Bounce off ceiling\n",
        "        if self.y - self.radius <= 0:\n",
        "            self.y = self.radius\n",
        "            self.vy = abs(self.vy) * FRICTION\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-consider}\n",
        "## 🤔 Consider This Corner\n",
        "\n",
        "**Why do we use `abs(self.vy)` when bouncing?**\n",
        "\n",
        "`abs()` makes the number positive. When hitting the floor, we want the ball to go up (negative vy), so we make it positive and then negate it: `-abs(self.vy)`.\n",
        "\n",
        "When hitting the right wall, we want it to go left (negative vx), so we make it positive: `abs(self.vx)`.\n",
        "\n",
        "This ensures the ball always bounces in the correct direction!\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "### Step 4: Draw the Ball with Velocity Vector\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "    def draw(self, surface):\n",
        "        \"\"\"Draw the ball on the given surface.\"\"\"\n",
        "        # Draw the ball\n",
        "        pygame.draw.circle(surface, self.color, \n",
        "                          (int(self.x), int(self.y)), \n",
        "                          self.radius)\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Draw velocity vector (shows movement direction)\n",
        "        end_x = int(self.x + self.vx * 3)\n",
        "        end_y = int(self.y + self.vy * 3)\n",
        "        pygame.draw.line(surface, WHITE, \n",
        "                        (int(self.x), int(self.y)), \n",
        "                        (end_x, end_y), 2)\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "The white line shows which way the ball is moving and how fast!\n",
        "\n",
        "### Step 5: Create the Main Game Loop\n",
        "\n",
        "```python\n",
        "def main():\n",
        "    \"\"\"Main game loop.\"\"\"\n",
        "    # Create window\n",
        "    screen = pygame.display.set_mode((WINDOW_WIDTH, WINDOW_HEIGHT))\n",
        "    pygame.display.set_caption(\"Day 02: Bouncing Ball Physics\")\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # Create clock\n",
        "    clock = pygame.time.Clock()\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # List to store all balls\n",
        "    balls = []\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # Create some initial balls\n",
        "    for _ in range(5):\n",
        "        x = random.randint(50, WINDOW_WIDTH - 50)\n",
        "        y = random.randint(50, 200)\n",
        "        radius = random.randint(15, 40)\n",
        "        color = random.choice(COLORS)\n",
        "        balls.append(Ball(x, y, radius, color))\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # Font for instructions\n",
        "    font = pygame.font.Font(None, 36)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # Main game loop\n",
        "    running = True\n",
        "    while running:\n",
        "        # Handle events\n",
        "        for event in pygame.event.get():\n",
        "            if event.type == pygame.QUIT:\n",
        "                running = False\n",
        "            \n",
        "            # Add ball on mouse click\n",
        "            elif event.type == pygame.MOUSEBUTTONDOWN:\n",
        "                x, y = event.pos\n",
        "                radius = random.randint(15, 40)\n",
        "                color = random.choice(COLORS)\n",
        "                balls.append(Ball(x, y, radius, color))\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Update all balls\n",
        "        for ball in balls:\n",
        "            ball.update()\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Draw everything\n",
        "        screen.fill(BLACK)\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Draw all balls\n",
        "        for ball in balls:\n",
        "            ball.draw(screen)\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Draw instructions\n",
        "        text = font.render(\"Click to add balls!\", True, WHITE)\n",
        "        screen.blit(text, (10, 10))\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Update display\n",
        "        pygame.display.flip()\n",
        "        clock.tick(FPS)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    pygame.quit()\n",
        "    sys.exit()\n",
        "\n",
        "if __name__ == \"__main__\":\n",
        "    main()\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 🎮 Try It Yourself!\n",
        "\n",
        "### Complete Code\n",
        "\n",
        "Create a new file `bouncing_ball.py` and copy the complete code from above, or use the provided template!\n",
        "\n",
        "### Running Your Game\n",
        "\n",
        "```bash\n",
        "cd Day_02\n",
        "uv sync\n",
        "uv run python src_instr/bouncing_ball.py\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "### What to Expect\n",
        "\n",
        "- Multiple colorful balls bouncing around\n",
        "- Each ball has a white line showing its velocity\n",
        "- Click anywhere to spawn new balls!\n",
        "- Balls gradually slow down due to friction\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 🧪 Understanding the Physics\n",
        "\n",
        "### Gravity Simulation"
      ],
      "id": "59aeb64b"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "# Let's simulate different gravity values\n",
        "\n",
        "def test_gravity(gravity, frames=20):\n",
        "    \"\"\"Test how objects fall with different gravity\"\"\"\n",
        "    y = 0\n",
        "    vy = 0\n",
        "    \n",
        "    print(f\"\\nGravity = {gravity}\")\n",
        "    print(\"Frame | Y Position | Velocity\")\n",
        "    print(\"-\" * 35)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    for frame in range(frames):\n",
        "        if frame % 5 == 0:  # Print every 5th frame\n",
        "            print(f\"{frame:5} | {y:10.1f} | {vy:8.2f}\")\n",
        "        vy += gravity\n",
        "        y += vy\n",
        "\n",
        "# Test different gravity values\n",
        "test_gravity(0.5)   # Our game's gravity\n",
        "test_gravity(1.0)   # Double gravity\n",
        "test_gravity(0.25)  # Moon gravity!"
      ],
      "id": "c4d357f8",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "### Velocity Over Time"
      ],
      "id": "9773972e"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Simulate a bouncing ball\n",
        "def simulate_bouncing_ball(initial_vy=-15, friction=0.8, gravity=0.5, frames=100):\n",
        "    \"\"\"Simulate and plot ball position over time\"\"\"\n",
        "    y_positions = []\n",
        "    velocities = []\n",
        "    y = 300  # Start at middle\n",
        "    vy = initial_vy\n",
        "    \n",
        "    for _ in range(frames):\n",
        "        # Apply gravity\n",
        "        vy += gravity\n",
        "        y += vy\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Bounce off ground (y=600)\n",
        "        if y >= 600:\n",
        "            y = 600\n",
        "            vy = -abs(vy) * friction\n",
        "        \n",
        "        y_positions.append(y)\n",
        "        velocities.append(vy)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # Create plots\n",
        "    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10, 6))\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # Plot position\n",
        "    ax1.plot(y_positions, color='blue', linewidth=2)\n",
        "    ax1.set_ylabel('Y Position (pixels)')\n",
        "    ax1.set_title('Ball Position Over Time')\n",
        "    ax1.invert_yaxis()  # Flip so down is positive\n",
        "    ax1.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # Plot velocity\n",
        "    ax2.plot(velocities, color='red', linewidth=2)\n",
        "    ax2.set_xlabel('Frame')\n",
        "    ax2.set_ylabel('Velocity (pixels/frame)')\n",
        "    ax2.set_title('Ball Velocity Over Time')\n",
        "    ax2.axhline(y=0, color='black', linestyle='--', alpha=0.3)\n",
        "    ax2.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "    plt.show()\n",
        "    \n",
        "    return y_positions, velocities\n",
        "\n",
        "# Run simulation\n",
        "positions, velocities = simulate_bouncing_ball()\n",
        "print(f\"Ball bounced {sum(1 for v in velocities if v < 0 and velocities[velocities.index(v)-1] > 0)} times\")"
      ],
      "id": "1a561e52",
